        <name>W4 Q04 Lagrange - point to plane</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p&gt;Use Lagrange multipliers to find the distance from the point \( P=({@a@},{@b@},{@c@}) \) to the plane {@pl@} as follows.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Let \(f(x,y,z)\) be the square of the distance from \( (x,y,z) \) to \( P=({@a@},{@b@},{@c@}) \).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;\( f(x,y,x) = \) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Let \( g(x,y,z)=0 \) be the constraint that \((x,y,z)\) lies on {@pl@}.  We define the Lagrangian \[ L= f(x,y,z) + lg(x,y,z)\]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Calculate \( \frac{\partial L}{\partial x} = \) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Calculate \( \frac{\partial L}{\partial l} = \) [[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Solve the equations \( \frac{\partial L}{\partial x} = 0\),  \( \frac{\partial L}{\partial y} = 0\), \( \frac{\partial L}{\partial z} = 0\), \( \frac{\partial L}{\partial l} = 0\), and find the value of \(l\).&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;\( l= \) [[input:ans4]] [[validation:ans4]]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Hence, find the shortest distance from the point to the plane.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Shortest distance is  [[input:ans5]] [[validation:ans5]]&lt;/p&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>We define
\[ L= f(x,y,z) + lg(x,y,z)\]
In our case this gives us
\[ L = {@taf@} - l({@tag@}).\]
Now we calculate the derivatives as
\[ \frac{\partial L}{\partial x} = {@Lx@}\]
\[ \frac{\partial L}{\partial y} = {@Ly@}\]
\[ \frac{\partial L}{\partial z} = {@Lz@}\]
\[ \frac{\partial L}{\partial l} = {@Ll@}\]
Now we need to equate to zero and solve this system of algebraic equations.
\[ {@Lx@}=0,\quad {@Ly@}=0,\quad {@Lz@}=0,\quad {@Ll@}=0.\]
In this case, we can solve for \(x\), \(y\) and \(z\) which give us solutions in terms of \(l\).
\[ {@taxl@} \]
\[ {@tayl@} \]
\[ {@tazl@} \]
When we use these values in \({@Ll@}=0\) we get 
\[ {@L1@}=0.\]
Although this looks complicated it is a linear equation in \(l\) which we can readily solve to give \({@tal@}\).
So, this gives the actual values of \(x\), \(y\) and \(z\) as
\[ {@tax@}\]
\[ {@tay@}\]
\[ {@taz@}\]
Now, we need to evaluate \(f\) at this point to give us the square of the distance.
\[ f(x,y,z) = {@fv@}\]
So, the closest distance of \( P=({@a@},{@b@},{@c@}) \) to the plane {@pl@} is {@sqrt(fv)@}.</generalfeedback>
